<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910226-0127</DOCNO><DOCID>910226-0127.</DOCID><HL>   Credit Ratings:   Sandamp;P Lowers Rating   On Meritor Savings'   $115 Million of Debt</HL><DATE>02/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><CO>   MTOR</CO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)STOCK AND BOND RATINGS (RTG)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Standard andamp; Poor's Corp. said it lowered itsrating on Meritor Savings Bank's $115 million in subordinateddebt, following Meritor's plan to buy back the debt at asteep discount.   The ratings concern said Meritor's 12% subordinatedcapital notes, which are due in 1998 and payable in common orperpetual preferred stock, were lowered to double-C fromsingle-B-minus. The rating will be dropped to D if interestpayments due Friday aren't made, Sandamp;P added. Meritor announcedthe debt redemption proposal last week, and said regardlessof the outcome it would stop paying interest on the notes.</LP><TEXT>   Sandamp;P also noted fundamental problems with the bank,including expected continuing losses and problems with assetquality. It did say that tangible capital, while still weak,improved in 1990 through restructuring, including theshedding of many branches.   Meritor officials couldn't immediately be reached forcomment.</TEXT></DOC>